Here, we investigate the maximim number of real zeroes 
of a univariate polynomial of the form:

    f(z)*g(z)^p*z^l - h(z),

where f, g, h all have degree k.

  These come from the system consisting of 
the empty simplex     and the segment
  0101                        0  0  ...  0
  001p  where (p,q)=1         0  0  ...  0
  000q   &    p < q           0 -1  ... -k

The transformation z |--> z + k(1-x-y) and l:=q-pk-k > 0, gives

   0 0 ... 0 1 0 1        x = f(z)    \
   0 0 ... 0 0 1 p        y = g(z)     > f(z)*g(z)^p*z^(l+k) - h(z) = 0
   0 1 ... k 0 0 l  xy^pz^lz^k = h(z) /

These systems are most interesting when l > 1

When p = 1, it is easy to see that the maximum number of real solutions is

    3k + d, where d = 1 or 2, depending upon the parity of l.
